<!-- ══════════════ LESSON 01: HOW TO READ ══════════════ -->
<div class="sec lesson-section" id="l-reading">
  <span class="sec-num">§ 01 · LESSON</span>
  <h2>How to Read & Reference Singapore Tax Laws</h2>
  <div class="sec-rule"></div>
  <div class="case-bridge"><span class="cb-icon">📁</span><div><strong>Meridian Application:</strong> Every issue in the case study depends on locating the precise statutory provision. Issue 3 (non-deductibles) requires distinguishing <span class="prov">s14(1)(a)</span> from <span class="prov">s15(1)(b)(c)(f)</span>. Issue 1 requires reading <span class="prov">EEI Act s5</span> alongside the <span class="prov">BEPS Act</span>. Issue 14 turns on the exact wording of <span class="prov">s13(1)(za)</span> vs <span class="prov">s33</span>. See: <a href="#i3">Issue 3 →</a> <a href="#i1">Issue 1 →</a></div></div>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card"><div class="card-title">📖 Anatomy of a Statute</div>
      <p style="font-size:.84rem;margin-bottom:10px;">Singapore statutes follow a precise citation hierarchy:</p>
      <div class="calc"><span class="k">Act</span> → <span class="k">Part</span> → <span class="k">Division</span> → <span class="k">Section (s)</span>
  → <span class="k">Subsection (ss)</span> → <span class="k">Paragraph (para)</span>
<span class="c">// Example: ITA s10(1)(a)</span>
<span class="fn">ITA</span> <span class="op">s</span><span class="n">10</span>(<span class="n">1</span>)(<span class="op">a</span>) = <span class="res">"gains or profits from any trade..."</span></div>
    </div>
    <div class="card"><div class="card-title">🔗 Key Acts Quick Reference</div>
      <table class="tbl">
        <tr><th>Act</th><th>Cap.</th><th>Primary Tax</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Income Tax Act 1947</td><td><span class="tag tag-gold">134</span></td><td>Income, CIT, WHT</td></tr>
        <tr><td>GST Act 1993</td><td><span class="tag tag-b">117A</span></td><td>9% GST</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Stamp Duties Act 1929</td><td><span class="tag tag-r">312</span></td><td>BSD, ABSD, SSD</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Property Tax Act 1960</td><td><span class="tag tag-g">254</span></td><td>Annual Value tax</td></tr>
        <tr><td>EEI Act (Incentives)</td><td><span class="tag tag-gold">86</span></td><td>Pioneer, DEI</td></tr>
        <tr><td>BEPS (Min. Tax) Act</td><td>—</td><td>15% QDMTT</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="card"><div class="card-title">🔍 The Four-Step Reading Method</div>
    <div class="tab-row">
      <button class="tab-btn active" onclick="switchTab(this,'rt','r1')">1: Identify</button>
      <button class="tab-btn" onclick="switchTab(this,'rt','r2')">2: Charge First</button>
      <button class="tab-btn" onclick="switchTab(this,'rt','r3')">3: Definitions</button>
      <button class="tab-btn" onclick="switchTab(this,'rt','r4')">4: Purposive</button>
    </div>
    <div id="rt">
      <div class="tab-pnl active" id="r1"><p style="font-size:.88rem;"><strong style="color:var(--gold2);">Which Act governs?</strong> Income question → ITA. Supply of goods/services → GST Act. Property transfer → SDA. Property ownership → PTA. Read the <em>Arrangement of Sections</em> at the front. Multiple Acts may apply simultaneously to the same transaction — never assume one statute is exhaustive. In Meridian's property disposal (Issue 2), both ITA (income tax on gain) and SDA (Seller's Stamp Duty) apply independently.</p></div>
      <div class="tab-pnl" id="r2"><p style="font-size:.88rem;"><strong style="color:var(--gold2);">Always read the charging section first.</strong> ITA <span class="prov">s10(1)</span> — the eight heads of taxable income. Only after understanding the charge should you look for exemptions (<span class="prov">s13</span>) and deductions (<span class="prov">s14</span>). The default position is: <em>income is taxable unless exempt; expenses are non-deductible unless specifically allowed.</em> This asymmetry is fundamental — and the opposite of how most taxpayers naturally think.</p></div>
      <div class="tab-pnl" id="r3"><p style="font-size:.88rem;"><strong style="color:var(--gold2);">Check definitions before the provision.</strong> <span class="prov">ITA s2</span> defines "resident", "trade", "person", "chargeable income". "Resident" in ITA differs from "resident" in a DTA. A key error in the Meridian case: assuming "technical fees" under the Singapore-Vietnam DTA has the same meaning as "management fees" under domestic ITA. Always check: does this word have a statutory definition or a treaty-specific definition?</p></div>
      <div class="tab-pnl" id="r4"><p style="font-size:.88rem;"><strong style="color:var(--gold2);">Apply the purposive approach (<span class="prov">Interpretation Act s9A</span>).</strong> Singapore courts read statutes to fulfil Parliament's intent, not just the literal text. The dividend stripping issue (Issue 14) turns entirely on whether s13(1)(za)'s purpose was to exempt all one-tier dividends, or only <em>genuine</em> dividend distributions. The <span class="cite">CIT v AQQ [2014] SGCA</span> GAAR case is the landmark application of purposive construction in tax.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══════════════ LESSON 02: TAX STRUCTURE ══════════════ -->
<div class="sec lesson-section" id="l-structure">
  <span class="sec-num">§ 02 · LESSON</span>
  <h2>Singapore Tax Structure — All Taxes at a Glance</h2>
  <div class="sec-rule"></div>
  <div class="vn-bridge-block"><div class="vn-title">🇻🇳 VN Bridge — Territorial vs Worldwide</div><p style="font-size:.84rem;">Vietnam taxes residents on worldwide income. Singapore is <strong>strictly territorial</strong> — only income accruing in or derived from Singapore, or received in Singapore from abroad, is taxable under <span class="prov">ITA s10(1)</span>. There is <em>no capital gains tax, no inheritance tax, no dividend withholding tax</em> in Singapore. This creates massive planning opportunities — and the GAAR (s33) exists precisely to prevent abuse of these gaps.</p></div>
  <div class="case-bridge"><span class="cb-icon">📁</span><div><strong>Meridian Application:</strong> The territorial principle directly determines Issues 2 (property gain), 9 (royalty WHT), 10 (loan interest), 11 (treaty shopping), 12 (crypto gains). All five issues turn on whether income has a Singapore source or whether Singapore can tax a foreign receipt. <a href="#i2">Issue 2 →</a> <a href="#i9">Issue 9 →</a> <a href="#i11">Issue 11 →</a></div></div>
  <div class="grid3">
    <div class="card"><div class="card-title">🏢 CIT</div><p style="font-size:.82rem;"><strong style="color:var(--gold2);">17% flat</strong> (since YA 2010)<br>Pioneer: 0–10% under EEI Act<br>Partial exemption: <span class="prov">s43C</span><br>Startup exemption: <span class="prov">s43(6A)</span><br>Base: Chargeable Income</p></div>
    <div class="card"><div class="card-title">👤 PIT</div><p style="font-size:.82rem;"><strong style="color:var(--gold2);">Progressive to 22%</strong><br>Resident: <span class="prov">s43</span> rates<br>Non-resident: flat 22%<br>Key reliefs: <span class="prov">s39</span><br>CPF deductible: <span class="prov">s39(2)(g)</span></p></div>
    <div class="card"><div class="card-title">🛒 GST</div><p style="font-size:.82rem;"><strong style="color:var(--gold2);">9%</strong> since 1 Jan 2024<br>Threshold: S$1M turnover<br>Zero-rated: exports, intl services<br>Exempt: financial, residential<br>Partial exemption: <span class="prov">s26</span></p></div>
    <div class="card"><div class="card-title">🏠 Stamp Duty</div><p style="font-size:.82rem;"><strong style="color:var(--gold2);">BSD</strong>: 1–6% progressive<br><strong style="color:var(--gold2);">ABSD</strong>: 0–65% (entity: 65%)<br><strong style="color:var(--gold2);">SSD</strong>: up to 15% if sold &lt;3yr<br><span class="prov">SDA s22A–22C</span></p></div>
    <div class="card"><div class="card-title">🏘 Property Tax</div><p style="font-size:.82rem;">Based on <strong style="color:var(--gold2);">Annual Value (AV)</strong><br>Commercial: flat 10%<br>Owner-occ residential: 0–32%<br>Non-owner resi: 12–36%<br><span class="prov">PTA s6, s20</span></p></div>
    <div class="card"><div class="card-title">🌍 WHT</div><p style="font-size:.82rem;">Non-resident payments:<br>Royalties: <strong style="color:var(--gold2);">10%</strong><br>Interest: <strong style="color:var(--gold2);">15%</strong><br>Technical fees: <strong style="color:var(--gold2);">17%</strong><br>Director fees: <strong style="color:var(--gold2);">22%</strong><br><span class="prov">ITA s45</span></p></div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══════════════ LESSON 03: WATERFALL ══════════════ -->
<div class="sec lesson-section" id="l-waterfall">
  <span class="sec-num">§ 03 · LESSON</span>
  <h2>Legal Hierarchy — The Waterfall of Authority</h2>
  <div class="sec-rule"></div>
  <div class="case-bridge"><span class="cb-icon">📁</span><div><strong>Meridian Application:</strong> The waterfall is essential for resolving Issue 1 (BEPS Act vs EEI Act — which is higher authority?), Issue 9 (DTA Art. 12 vs domestic <span class="prov">s45</span> WHT rate), and Issue 11 (MLI PPT vs bilateral DTA). The answer to each conflict requires first establishing <em>where each instrument sits in the waterfall</em>. <a href="#i1">Issue 1 →</a> <a href="#i9">Issue 9 →</a> <a href="#i11">Issue 11 →</a></div></div>
  <div class="wfall">
    <div class="wf-item"><div class="wf-conn"><div class="wf-dot">1</div><div class="wf-line"></div></div><div class="wf-body"><div class="wf-level">APEX</div><div class="wf-title">Constitution of Singapore</div><p>Art. 89: Parliament has plenary taxing power. Art. 12: equal treatment. No tax can violate fundamental liberties. In Meridian, an argument that the BEPS Act unconstitutionally impairs the Pioneer certificate would need to overcome Art. 89's breadth — a near-impossible task.</p></div></div>
    <div class="wf-item"><div class="wf-conn"><div class="wf-dot">2</div><div class="wf-line"></div></div><div class="wf-body"><div class="wf-level">INTERNATIONAL</div><div class="wf-title">Double Tax Agreements (DTAs) & MLI</div><p>Singapore's 100+ DTAs are given effect via <span class="prov">ITA s49</span>. DTAs <em>relieve</em> domestic tax charges but cannot <em>create</em> them. The MLI (BEPS Multilateral Instrument) modifies bilateral DTAs — its Principal Purpose Test (Art. 7) can deny treaty benefits if tax was a principal purpose of the arrangement. Meridian Issues 9 and 11 both turn on the MLI PPT.</p></div></div>
    <div class="wf-item"><div class="wf-conn"><div class="wf-dot">3</div><div class="wf-line"></div></div><div class="wf-body"><div class="wf-level">PRIMARY</div><div class="wf-title">Acts of Parliament (Tax Statutes)</div><p>ITA, GST Act, SDA, PTA, EEI Act, BEPS Act. Lex specialis (specific) prevails over lex generalis (general). Lex posterior (later Act) generally prevails when two Acts conflict equally. <span class="prov">ITA s5</span> explicitly states ITA is subject to EEI Act — statutory cross-referencing. The BEPS Act (2024) is a new, separate Act — not an amendment of EEI Act.</p></div></div>
    <div class="wf-item"><div class="wf-conn"><div class="wf-dot">4</div><div class="wf-line"></div></div><div class="wf-body"><div class="wf-level">SUBSIDIARY</div><div class="wf-title">Regulations, Rules & Orders</div><p>Made under parent Act powers. Must not exceed the parent Act scope (ultra vires = void). Examples: Income Tax (Exemption) Orders, GST (General) Regulations, ABSD Remission Rules. Must be read with the parent Act — they qualify but cannot contradict.</p></div></div>
    <div class="wf-item"><div class="wf-conn"><div class="wf-dot">5</div><div class="wf-line"></div></div><div class="wf-body"><div class="wf-level">ADMINISTRATIVE</div><div class="wf-title">IRAS e-Tax Guides, Circulars & Advance Rulings</div><p>Not legally binding on courts, but IRAS is bound by its own guidance via legitimate expectation. Advance rulings (<span class="prov">ITA s108</span>) are binding on IRAS for stated transactions. The Meridian crypto issue (Issue 12) has no e-Tax Guide covering DeFi — highlighting the danger of operating in guidance gaps.</p></div></div>
    <div class="wf-item"><div class="wf-conn"><div class="wf-dot">6</div><div class="wf-line" style="background:transparent;"></div></div><div class="wf-body"><div class="wf-level">INTERPRETIVE</div><div class="wf-title">Case Law — ITBR, High Court, Court of Appeal</div><p>ITBR decisions are persuasive. High Court and Court of Appeal are binding. Key cases from Meridian: <span class="cite">CIT v AQQ [2014] SGCA</span> (GAAR counterfactual), <span class="cite">BFC v CIT [2013] SGCA</span> (source of income), <span class="cite">AQP v CIT [2013] SGITBR</span> (trading vs capital).</p></div></div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══════════════ LESSON 04: CONFLICT ══════════════ -->
<div class="sec lesson-section" id="l-conflict">
  <span class="sec-num">§ 04 · LESSON</span>
  <h2>Conflict, Overlap & Priority Rules</h2>
  <div class="sec-rule"></div>
  <div class="case-bridge"><span class="cb-icon">📁</span><div><strong>Meridian Application:</strong> Every one of Meridian's 15 issues involves a conflict between provisions. The most consequential: s14 vs s15 (Issue 3), BEPS Act vs EEI Act (Issue 1), s13(1)(za) vs s33 (Issue 14), DTA Art. 12 vs MLI PPT (Issue 9), ITA s10(1)(a)/(b) vs PWA 2024 (Issue 13). The resolution methodology below is your toolkit for all 15. <a href="#i3">I3</a> · <a href="#i1">I1</a> · <a href="#i14">I14</a> · <a href="#i9">I9</a> · <a href="#i13">I13</a></div></div>
  <div class="tab-row"><button class="tab-btn active" onclick="switchTab(this,'ct','ct1')">Within ITA</button><button class="tab-btn" onclick="switchTab(this,'ct','ct2')">ITA ↔ GST</button><button class="tab-btn" onclick="switchTab(this,'ct','ct3')">Tax ↔ DTA</button><button class="tab-btn" onclick="switchTab(this,'ct','ct4')">GAAR</button><button class="tab-btn" onclick="switchTab(this,'ct','ct5')">Multi-Act</button></div>
  <div id="ct">
    <div class="tab-pnl active" id="ct1">
      <div class="box box-conflict"><div class="box-title">s14(1)(a) vs s15(1)(b)(c)(f) — Deductibility Battlefield</div><p>s14 grants deductions for expenses "wholly and exclusively" incurred in producing income. s15 <em>prohibits</em> specific categories regardless of s14. <strong>Resolution: s15 always wins.</strong> The "notwithstanding" structure of s15 makes it a trump card. In Meridian Issue 3, every single disputed expense is caught by s15 — entertainment (b), fines (f), goodwill (c), IPO costs (c), club membership (b). <mark class="bad">Non-deductible: S$2,017,500</mark></p></div>
      <div class="box box-conflict" style="margin-top:10px;"><div class="box-title">s10(1) (Charge) vs s13 (Exemption) — Default Position</div><p>The charge under s10(1) applies by default. Exemptions under s13 must be <em>claimed</em> and <em>proven</em>. Exemptions are read narrowly — the taxpayer bears the burden. In Issue 14, s13(1)(za) dividend exemption is a specific exemption that Meridian must prove applies; IRAS can challenge it under s33 GAAR.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="tab-pnl" id="ct2">
      <div class="box box-conflict"><div class="box-title">ITA deductibility ≠ GST input tax recovery — Independent Regimes</div><p>The same expense may be ITA-deductible but GST-blocked (e.g., entertainment: ITA non-deductible AND GST input blocked under Fourth Schedule para 1(e)). Or GST-recoverable but ITA non-deductible (e.g., capital expenditure on plant — ITA disallows but capital allowances apply; GST input fully recoverable). Compute each independently. In Issue 3/5, the gala dinner fails both tests via different statutory paths — illustrating "convergent denial."</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="tab-pnl" id="ct3">
      <div class="box box-conflict"><div class="box-title">DTA Art. 12 (Royalties) vs ITA s45 WHT Rate</div><p>Domestic rate (s45): 10% on royalties to non-residents. DTA reduced rate: 8% (Singapore-UK). The DTA relief is available only if (i) the recipient is a tax resident of the other contracting state, AND (ii) the recipient is the beneficial owner of the royalties. In Meridian Issue 9, Meridian UK may not be the beneficial owner — making the 8% rate unavailable and the domestic 10% applicable. The MLI PPT test provides an additional layer of challenge.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="tab-pnl" id="ct4">
      <div class="box box-conflict"><div class="box-title">ITA s33 GAAR — The Override That Knows No Limits</div><p>s33 allows IRAS to disregard, vary, or counteract any arrangement that has the effect of reducing, avoiding, or deferring tax, where the arrangement would not have been entered into but for the tax benefit (counterfactual test from <span class="cite">CIT v AQQ</span>). s33 can override: specific exemptions (s13), specific deductions (s14), treaty benefits (s49 — controversial), incentive rates (EEI Act). In Meridian, Issues 11 (treaty shopping) and 14 (dividend strip) are both potential s33 targets.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="tab-pnl" id="ct5">
      <div class="box box-conflict"><div class="box-title">ITA vs Companies Act / PWA / CPF Act — Cross-Statute Conflicts</div><p>Each statute applies independently within its own domain. A payment classified as a "return of capital" under Companies Act can still be income under ITA. A worker classified as a "platform worker" under PWA 2024 (MOM) is still either s10(1)(a) or s10(1)(b) income for ITA. The CPF Act imposes contribution obligations that the ITA s14(1)(c) deductibility provision may not accommodate if the worker isn't legally an "employee." Meridian Issue 13 sits exactly in this cross-statute gap.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ══════════════ LESSON 05: CALENDAR ══════════════ -->
<div class="sec lesson-section" id="l-calendar">
  <span class="sec-num">§ 05 · LESSON</span>
  <h2>Singapore Tax Compliance Calendar</h2>
  <div class="sec-rule"></div>
  <div class="case-bridge"><span class="cb-icon">📁</span><div><strong>Meridian Application:</strong> Meridian's compliance failures are calendar failures. The director fees WHT (Issue 15) should have been withheld and remitted within 30 days of payment. The Vietnam management fee WHT (Issue 4) — same. ECI filing for Meridian's December year-end is due by 31 March. Missing these deadlines triggers <span class="prov">ITA s94</span> penalties (5% surcharge) and <span class="prov">s45(4)</span> WHT surcharges. <a href="#i4">Issue 4 →</a> <a href="#i15">Issue 15 →</a></div></div>
  <div class="cal-grid">
    <div class="cal-mon"><div class="cal-mon-hdr">JAN–FEB</div>
      <div class="cal-item"><div class="cd">15 Jan</div>GST F5 (quarterly Oct–Dec)</div>
      <div class="cal-item urg"><div class="cd">28 Feb</div>IR8A/IR8E — employer AIS submission</div>
