    <tfoot><tr><td><strong>Total crypto tax exposure (IRAS likely)</strong></td><td class="nc neg"><strong>≈S$459,000</strong></td><td colspan="2">at 17% on ~S$2.7M taxable gains</td></tr></tfoot>
  </table>
  <div class="box box-unresolved"><div class="box-title">DeFi Yield Farming — Singapore's Most Significant Tax Black Hole</div><p>Yield farming rewards (S$120,000 in UNI governance tokens): <strong>(a) When recognised?</strong> At receipt (illiquid, volatile) or at sale (realisation)? <strong>(b) Tax base?</strong> Market value at receipt — creates tax liability on amounts that may become worthless. <strong>(c) Is staking a GST supply?</strong> If yield farming is a financial service (lending crypto to a pool), it may be GST-exempt; if a goods supply, standard-rated. No IRAS guidance on any of these points. <strong>Best practice 2025: apply conservative s10(1)(g) treatment, recognise at receipt at market value, file a query to IRAS for advance guidance under ITA s108.</strong></p></div>
</div>

<!-- ══════════════ ISSUE 13 ══════════════ -->
<div class="issue-wrap case-section" id="i13">
  <div class="issue-hdr"><span class="issue-num-badge">ISSUE 13 · CPF+ITA</span><div><div class="issue-title">3,200 Platform Workers — PWA 2024 vs ITA Classification Paradox & CPF Deductibility</div><div class="issue-sub">ITA s10(1)(a)/(b) · CPF Act s7 · Platform Workers Act 2024 (MOM) · ITA s14(1)(c)</div></div></div>
  <div class="lesson-bridge"><span class="lb-icon">📚</span><div><strong>Lesson Foundation:</strong> This is the real-world application of <strong>§04 Conflict</strong> (Multi-Act tab — ITA vs labour law) and <strong>§07 Dilemmas</strong> (Issue 2 — gig economy). The ITA has not been amended to accommodate the PWA 2024's new worker category. Until it is, two independent statutes produce inconsistent classifications — a legislative gap that Meridian must navigate in live compliance.</div></div>
  <div class="calc"><span class="lbl">// CPF OBLIGATIONS — Platform Workers (FY 2025 onward under PWA 2024)</span>
<span class="c">// Phase-in rates (employer contributions):</span>
<span class="c">// 2025: 3.5%  |  2026: 5.5%  |  2027: 7.5%  |  2028: 9%  (full phase-in)</span>
<span class="k">Qualifying_Workers</span>     ≈ <span class="n">800</span>   <span class="c">// earning >S$6K/year from platform</span>
<span class="k">Est_Qualifying_Income</span>  = <span class="n">800</span> <span class="op">×</span> <span class="n">~S$36,000/yr</span>  = <span class="n">28,800,000</span>

<span class="k">Employer_CPF_2025</span>      = <span class="n">28,800,000</span> <span class="op">×</span> <span class="n">3.5%</span>  = <span class="res">S$1,008,000</span>  <span class="c">// new cost to Meridian Gig</span>
<span class="k">Employer_CPF_2029</span>      = <span class="n">28,800,000</span> <span class="op">×</span> <span class="n">9.0%</span>  = <span class="res">S$2,592,000</span>  <span class="c">// full phase-in</span>

<span class="c">// ITA deductibility question (ITA s14(1)(c)):</span>
<span class="c">// s14(1)(c) allows deduction for CPF contributions "in respect of employees"</span>
<span class="c">// Platform workers = NOT employees under ITA (they are s10(1)(a) self-employed)</span>
<span class="c">// → CPF contributions by platform operator may NOT be deductible under s14(1)(c)</span>
<span class="res">// UNRESOLVED: Creates S$1M+ non-deductible cost from 2025</span></div>
  <div class="box box-conflict"><div class="box-title">⚡ The PWA 2024 / ITA Paradox</div><p>MOM says: Meridian Gig must make CPF contributions for qualifying platform workers (like an employer). ITA says: platform workers are self-employed (s10(1)(a)), not employees — no employment relationship. <span class="prov">ITA s14(1)(c)</span> deductibility requires "employees." If workers are not employees under ITA, the CPF contribution is non-deductible — a permanent tax cost of up to S$2.6M/year at full phase-in. Parliament has not amended ITA to create a corresponding deduction for PWA CPF contributions. Meridian's legal team must decide: (a) treat workers as employees for ITA (creates other complications) or (b) treat as self-employed and accept non-deductible CPF contributions.</p></div>
</div>

<!-- ══════════════ ISSUE 14 ══════════════ -->
<div class="issue-wrap case-section" id="i14">
  <div class="issue-hdr"><span class="issue-num-badge">ISSUE 14 · GAAR</span><div><div class="issue-title">Dividend Stripping — ITA s33 vs s13(1)(za): The Most Dangerous Transaction in the Case</div><div class="issue-sub">ITA s33 · s13(1)(za) (one-tier dividend exemption) · CIT v AQQ [2014] SGCA · Parliamentary intent</div></div></div>
  <div class="lesson-bridge"><span class="lb-icon">📚</span><div><strong>Lesson Foundation:</strong> This is the pinnacle application of <strong>§03 Waterfall</strong> (Level 5 — IRAS administrative position vs courts) and <strong>§04 Conflict</strong> (GAAR tab — s33 vs specific exemption provisions). The one-tier dividend system (s13(1)(za)) sits at Level 3 (primary legislation). Section 33 GAAR also sits at Level 3. Two primary legislative provisions in conflict — resolved only by parliamentary intent, the purposive approach (<strong>§01 Reading, Step 4</strong>), and the SGCA counterfactual test.</div></div>
  <div class="box box-fact"><div class="box-title">The Arrangement — Classic Dividend Strip</div>
    <p>1. Meridian acquires TechCo (100%) for S$20,000,000. TechCo has S$8,000,000 retained earnings.<br>
    2. TechCo immediately declares S$8,000,000 dividend → Meridian receives tax-free under <span class="prov">s13(1)(za)</span>.<br>
    3. TechCo's net assets now = ~S$12,000,000. Meridian sells TechCo for S$12,000,000.<br>
    4. Net economic result: S$20M out → S$8M dividend + S$12M sale proceeds = S$20M in. Zero economic gain. But S$8M extracted tax-free from TechCo's retained earnings.</p></div>
  <div class="box box-issue"><div class="box-title">The Core Legal Conflict</div>
    <p><strong>Taxpayer's argument:</strong> Parliament designed the one-tier system to prevent double taxation. TechCo's earnings were already taxed at corporate level. The S$8M dividend is exactly what s13(1)(za) was designed to exempt. Meridian is simply using the law as written.</p>
    <p><strong>IRAS's argument (s33 GAAR):</strong> The counterfactual test: <em>would Meridian have acquired and immediately divested TechCo but for the tax benefit of extracting S$8M tax-free?</em> The answer is no — the transaction has zero commercial purpose beyond extracting retained earnings. s33 applies to "disregard or vary" the arrangement.</p></div>
  <div class="box box-critical"><div class="box-title">Critical Thinking: Parliamentary Intent vs Tax Avoidance</div><p style="font-size:.87rem;">The one-tier system was designed for genuine dividend distributions — a company distributing organic profits to long-term shareholders. It was not designed for the acquisition of a company <em>specifically</em> to extract its accumulated profits and immediately sell the shell. The absence of a specific dividend-stripping provision (unlike Australia's s45B ITAA 1997) means s33 GAAR must carry the entire anti-avoidance load. But s33's "dominant purpose" test is broader than Australia's specific provision — potentially reaching genuine dividend transactions. The risk of over-breadth is the main argument against applying s33 here. <strong>This issue has not been judicially decided in Singapore on analogous facts. Until it is, Meridian faces a binary outcome: either S$0 tax (s13(1)(za) applies) or S$1,360,000+ tax (S$8M deemed income × 17% at standard rate).</strong></p></div>
</div>

<!-- ══════════════ ISSUE 15 ══════════════ -->
<div class="issue-wrap case-section" id="i15">
  <div class="issue-hdr"><span class="issue-num-badge">ISSUE 15 · WHT+PIT</span><div><div class="issue-title">Non-Resident French Director Fees — WHT 22%, No DTA Reduction, A Very Common Error</div><div class="issue-sub">ITA s45(4) · SG-France DTA Art. 16 vs Art. 15 · 183-Day Exemption NOT applicable</div></div></div>
  <div class="lesson-bridge"><span class="lb-icon">📚</span><div><strong>Lesson Foundation:</strong> This applies <strong>§02 Tax Structure</strong> (WHT — director fees at 22%) and critically <strong>§01 Reading Step 2</strong> (always read the charging provision precisely — Art. 16 of DTAs is a distinct provision from Art. 15 Employment and does not contain the 183-day exemption). The common mistake is conflating the Art. 15 "short-stay" exemption with Art. 16 director fees. This misreading has cost Meridian S$26,400 in WHT plus penalties.</div></div>
  <div class="calc"><span class="lbl">// WHT — Non-Resident Director Fees (ITA s45(4))</span>
<span class="k">Director_Fees</span>          = <span class="n">120,000</span>
<span class="k">WHT_Rate</span>               = <span class="n">22%</span>         <span class="c">// ITA s45(4) — current PIT top rate</span>
<span class="k">WHT_Required</span>           = <span class="n">120,000</span> <span class="op">×</span> <span class="n">22%</span>   = <span class="res">S$26,400</span>

<span class="c">// SG-France DTA Art. 16: "Directors' fees paid by a SG-resident company to a France-resident director"</span>
<span class="c">// Art. 16 PRESERVES Singapore's right to tax — NO reduction in WHT rate</span>
<span class="c">// The 183-day exemption (DTA Art. 15) does NOT apply to director fees (Art. 15 ≠ Art. 16)</span>
<span class="k">DTA_Benefit</span>            = <span class="res">NONE</span>        <span class="c">// Art. 16 is an exception to Art. 15 short-stay exemption</span>

<span class="c">// Meridian's failure to withhold — cascading consequences</span>
<span class="k">Unpaid_WHT</span>             = <span class="n">26,400</span>
<span class="k">Surcharge_ITA_s45(4)</span>   = <span class="n">26,400</span> <span class="op">×</span> <span class="n">5%</span>    = <span class="n">1,320</span>
<span class="k">Late_Interest_Est</span>      = <span class="n">26,400</span> <span class="op">×</span> <span class="n">8%</span>    = <span class="n">2,112</span>
<span class="k">Total_Exposure_Issue15</span> = <span class="n">26,400</span> <span class="op">+</span> <span class="n">1,320</span> <span class="op">+</span> <span class="n">2,112</span> = <span class="res">S$29,832</span>

<span class="c">// Additional: deductibility of director fees (ITA s14(1)(a))</span>
<span class="c">// May be denied until WHT is properly remitted (ITA s45(5))</span></div>
</div>

