  {q:"Meridian Holdings pays director fees of S$120,000 to Isabelle Fontaine, a French national non-resident, who attends only 12 days of board meetings in Singapore. Does the Singapore-France DTA 183-day exemption (typically found in Art. 15 Employment Income) reduce the WHT rate on these director fees?",opts:["Yes — 12 days well below 183 days, so WHT is waived entirely","Yes — DTA Art. 15 reduces the rate to 5%","No — DTA Art. 16 (Director Fees) preserves Singapore's right to tax at domestic rates regardless of days present","No — director fees are exempt from WHT under ITA s13"],ans:2,d:'hard',pts:15,neg:5,src:'Issue 15 + Lesson §02',exp:"DTA Art. 16 (Director Fees) is a distinct provision from Art. 15 (Employment Income). Art. 15 contains the 183-day short-stay exemption. Art. 16 does NOT contain this exemption — it expressly preserves the source country (Singapore's) right to tax director fees from a Singapore-resident company, regardless of the number of days the director is present in Singapore. WHT at 22% applies in full."},
  {q:"Under the Singapore legal hierarchy, which principle governs when two Acts of Parliament — a specific tax statute and a general commercial law — conflict?",opts:["Lex posterior — the later statute always prevails","Lex superior — Parliament's constitutional taxing power always wins","Lex specialis — the specific tax statute prevails over the general commercial law","Lex communis — international treaties always override domestic Acts"],ans:2,d:'medium',pts:10,neg:5,src:'Lesson §03',exp:"Lex specialis derogat legi generali: specific legislation overrides general legislation. The ITA as a specific tax statute prevails over, say, the Companies Act in matters of income characterisation. This is why a payment classified as a return of capital under the Companies Act can still be taxable income under ITA s10(1)."},
